Prior to discussing the conjugable words , a brief note about stem forms . Conjugative suffixes and auxiliary verbs are attached to the stem forms of the affixee . In modern Japanese there 
are the following six stem forms . Imperfective form ( &#x672A ; &#x7136 ; &#x5F62 ; mizenkei )   is used for plain negative ( of verbs ) , causative and passive constructions . The most 
common use of this form is with the -nai auxiliary that turns verbs into their negative ( predicate ) form . ( See Verbs below . ) Continuative form ( &#x9023 ; &#x7528 ; &#x5F62 ; ren ' 
y&#x14D ; kei )   is used in a linking role . This is the most productive stem form , taking on a variety of endings and auxiliaries , and can even occur independently in a sense similar 
to the -te ending . This form is also used to negate adjectives . Terminal form ( &#x7D42 ; &#x6B62 ; &#x5F62 ; sh&#x16B ; shikei )   is used at the ends of clauses in predicate positions 
. This form is also variously known as plain form ( &#x57FA ; &#x672C ; &#x5F62 ; kihonkei ) or dictionary form ( &#x8F9E ; &#x66F8 ; &#x5F62 ; jishokei ) . Attributive form ( &#x9023 ; 
&#x4F53 ; &#x5F62 ; rentaikei )   in modern Japanese is practically identical to the terminal form ( but see Adjectives , below ) , but differs in use : it is prefixed to nominals and 
is used to define or classify the noun . In this function , the root of this stem form is called a prenominal adjective ( &#x9023 ; &#x4F53 ; &#x8A5E ; rentaishi ) . Hypothetical form ( 
&#x4EEE ; &#x5B9A ; &#x5F62 ; kateikei )   is used for conditional and subjunctive forms , using the -ba or -domo ending . Imperative form ( &#x547D ; &#x4EE4 ; &#x5F62 ; meireikei )   
is used to turn verbs into commands . Adjectives do not have an imperative stem form . The application of conjugative suffixes to stem forms follow certain euphonic principles ( &#x97F3 ; 
&#x4FBF ; onbin ) , which is discussed below . Verbs in Japanese are rigidly constrained to the ends of clauses in what is known as the predicate position . &#x732B ; &#x3000 ; &#x306F ; 
&#x9B5A ; &#x3092 ; &#x98DF ; &#x3079 ; &#x308B ; &#x3002 ; neko wa sakana o taberu Cats TOPIC fish OBJECT eat Cats eat fish . The subject and objects of the verb are indicated by means of 
particles ( see the section below ) , and the grammatical functions of the verb—primarily tense and voice—are indicated by means of conjugation . When the subject and the dissertative 
topic coincide , the subject is often omitted ; if the verb is intransitive , the entire sentence may consist of a single verb . Verbs have two tenses indicated by conjugation — past and 
nonpast . The semantic difference between present and future is not indicated by means of conjugation . Usually there is no ambiguity because few verbs can operate in both uses . Voice and 
aspect are also indicated by means of conjugation , and possibly agglutinating auxiliary verbs . For example , the continuative aspect is formed by means of the continuative conjugation 
known as the gerundive or -te form , and the auxiliary verb iru ; to illustrate , &#x898B ; &#x308B ; ( miru , to see ) → &#x898B ; &#x3066 ; &#x3044 ; &#x308B ; ( mite-iru , is seeing 
) . Verbs can be semantically classified based on certain conjugations . Stative verbs  indicate existential properties , such as to be ( &#x3044 ; &#x308B ; iru ) , can do ( &#x51FA ; 
&#x6765 ; &#x308B ; dekiru ) , need ( &#x8981 ; &#x308B ; iru ) , etc . These verbs generally do n't have a continuative conjugation with -iru because they are semantically continuative already 
. Continual verbs  conjugate with the auxiliary -iru to indicate the progressive aspect . Examples : to eat ( &#x98DF ; &#x3079 ; &#x308B ; taberu ) , to drink ( &#x98F2 ; &#x3080 ; nomu ) , 
to think ( &#x8003 ; &#x3048 ; &#x308B ; kangaeru ) . To illustrate the conjugation , &#x98DF ; &#x3079 ; &#x308B ; ( taberu , to eat ) → &#x98DF ; &#x3079 ; &#x3066 ; &#x3044 ; &#x308B ; 
( tabete-iru , is eating ) . Punctual verbs  conjugate with -iru to indicate a repeated action , or a continuing state after some action . Example : &#x77E5 ; &#x308B ; ( shiru , to know ) 
